manufacturerProductDescription.media_text: Free to Fly Take apart dinosaur toys Best Educational Kids toddler toys to develope brain, inspire their imagination. Researchers all agree that learning through play is key to a child’s healthy development. Free to Fly gives your kids both learning and play.Explore the dinosaur world together and spend hours of entertainment.

Velociraptor Velociraptor sickle-clawed dinosaur that flourished in central and eastern Asia during the Late Cretaceous Period (99 million to 65 million years ago). It is closely related to the North American Deinonychus of the Early Cretaceous in that both reptiles were dromaeosaurs. Velociraptor was smaller than Deinonychus, reaching a length of only 1.8 metres (6 feet) and perhaps weighing no more than 45 kg (100 pounds). Tyrannosaurus rex Tyrannosaurus rex was a genus of theropod dinosaur. The species Tyrannosaurus rex , commonly abbreviated to T. rex, is a fixture in popular culture. It lived throughout what is now western North America, with a much wider range than other tyrannosaurids. Fossils are found in a variety of rock formations dating to the last three million years of the Cretaceous Period, approximately 68 to 65 million years ago. Triceratops Triceratops is a genus of herbivorous ceratopsid dinosaur that first appeared during the late Maastrichtian stage of the late Cretaceous period,about 68 million years ago in what is now North America.Triceratops species possessed a sturdy build,with strong limbs,short hands with three hooves each,and short feet with four hooves each.

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on December 16, 2023
reviews.reviewTitle: 5.0 out of 5 stars Great gift for my grandson!
reviews.reviewText: I like that this dinosaur assembly included an electric screw driver (batteries included) that actually worked, and came with interchangeable blade and Phillips tips. My 4 y.o. grandson used it to assemble the dinosaurs as I helped him position the pieces, and immediately caught on to the forward and reverse buttons on the driver. The driver even has a slip clutch so the plastic screws don't get over-tightened.The dinosaur necks, jaws, tails and legs all have some movement and provided for some interesting play fighting between them.The plastic parts seem quite durable, and overall I'm pleased with the quality.

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on January 24, 2024
reviews.reviewText: I bought this for my son last. He loves take it apart and putting it back together, both with the drill and the screw driver. Easy to use and lots of fun.

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on January 22, 2024
reviews.reviewText: My almost 3 year old son absolutely loves these. He enjoys taking things apart and putting things back together so this is perfect for him. The drill and screwdrivers are easy to use.

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on January 9, 2024
reviews.reviewText: Not to hard to assemble. I had to help grandson, had to look at photos on box to assemble.

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on January 2, 2024
reviews.reviewText: These are adorable! My husband was able to put them together with my 3yr old. He used the drill. Great little project.

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on January 1, 2024
reviews.reviewText: This is an awesome toy, just don’t expect the instructions to help you. Yoo need a microscope to even see them, and then after all that trouble it’s just an ad for “Wuhan Labs”.Seriously, this is a great toy. Something for a dad and son, or grandpa and son to sit down with and enjoy. You basically look at the pieces and figure out how to build the dinosaurs using either included hand tools (Phillips screwdriver) or a power driver (it even has a clutch). And not to be sexist, there’s no reason a mom and daughter couldn’t enjoy it too. In my case, my daughter looked at the lacking instructions and said to me, “Here you go”.

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on February 8, 2024
reviews.reviewTitle: 5.0 out of 5 stars My 4 year old son LOVES this!
reviews.reviewText: I bought this as a Christmas present for my four-year-old son. He absolutely loves this toy. Everyone who sees it is amazed that the drill is actually a functioning drill.

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on December 5, 2023
reviews.reviewText: The idea of the product is great for ages 4-8 or 9 years old. It needs better step-by-step instructions. We had to google a video to assemble it. The feet do not assemble/construct properly to the legs. The pieces of the feet do not align properly to fit correctly to the legs. Tried several ways to assemble it. Not able to see a finished product. Would not recommend this toy set.
